To accomplish the task, you can create an HTML file named `portfolio.html` with the following content:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta http-equiv="X-UA-Compatible" content="IE=edge">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>My Portfolio</title>
</head>
<body>
    <header>
        <h1>My Portfolio</h1>
        <nav>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="#home">Home</a></li>
                <li><a href="#about">About</a></li>
                <li><a href="#projects">Projects</a></li>
            </ul>
        </nav>
    </header>

    <section id="home">
        <h2>Home</h2>
        <p>Welcome to my portfolio website!</p>
    </section>

    <section id="about">
        <h2>About</h2>
        <p>Learn more about me and my skills.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="projects">
        <h2>Projects</h2>
        <ul>
            <li>Project 1</li>
            <li>Project 2</li>
            <li>Project 3</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</body>
</html>
```

In this HTML file:
- The `<header>` contains the navigation menu with links to different sections.
- Each section (`<section>`) corresponds to a different part of the portfolio (Home, About, Projects) with headings and brief descriptions.
- The "Projects" section includes an unordered list of projects.
- Links in the navigation menu allow users to navigate to the respective sections within the page.
